<div class="instructions">
  <h3>First, you'll need to</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Create an application at <a href="http://twitter.com/apps/new" target="_blank">http://twitter.com/apps/new</a></li>
    <li>Configure <b>Callback URL</b> as <b><%= callback_url_for(f.object) %></b></li>
    <li>Check the box for <b>Use Twitter for login</b></li>
    <li>Save your application</li>
    <li>Twitter will provide you with the information we require below</li>
  </ol>
</div>
<p>
  <%= f.label :key, "Consumer Key" %><br />
  <%= f.text_field :key %>
</p>
<p>
  <%= f.label :secret, "Consumer Secret" %><br />
  <%= f.text_field :secret %>
</p>
<p>
  <%= f.label :icon, "Login button" %> <span class="hint">it is really better to download, resize &amp; host this yourself</span><br />
  <%= f.text_field :icon, :value => f.object.icon || 'http://a0.twimg.com/a/1255724203/images/twitter_logo_header.png' %>
</p>
<%= f.hidden_field :name, :value => "Twitter" %>
<%= f.hidden_field :callback_url, :value => callback_url_for(f.object) %>

<div class="instructions">
  <p>
    If you do not wish to use the site embed (aka multiple-services selector),
    you may redirect your user to this authentication service directly
    using the URL below:
  </p>
  <p>
    <code title='triple-click to select the full url'><%=h url_for(:controller => 'loginsane', :action => 'twitter_redirect', :id => @service.id, :only_path => false) %></code>
  </p>
</div>
